4 I've been lucky enough to visit Italy and try authentic Italian pizza. While I have tried the Napolean pizza, I will say that it was in Rome and not Naples, but that didn't seem to make a difference in taste to me. Needless to say, the pizza I had in Rome was the pizza I use to weigh against any other slice of pizza. Pomo Pizzeria has come pretty darn close to authentic pizza in my book.   I'm late in the Pomo Pizzeria game and just visited recently. This is hard to admit especially since the restaurant is in close vicinity to my home. Since the weather is so nice, I was looking for a place with a patio where we could sit and enjoy the last remaining days of cool weather. The patio at Pomo is relatively small so they had about a thirty minute wait which was well worth it for us since we were in no hurry. So we set up shop at the bar for a glass of wine while we waited. The wine was quite tasty! We ordered a house cab and for $6.75, it was a pretty decent glass of wine. About thirty minutes later, we got seated on the patio and the meal began!   Be warned that the patio is intimate and if you need to have a private conversation without a third party peeking in, I'd choose another location in the restaurant. It's authentic to European dining in that sense and we were in very close vicinity to our neighbors. We started with the bruschetta and Cesar salad (Romana) to share. The salad is huge and you could probably share it with two to three other people. It was zesty, creamy and delicious. The order of bruschetta gave us two pieces of bread heaping with tomatoes. If you are with a party of more than two, I'd suggest ordering two orders of bruschetta or you can cut each slice in half. So the meal was off to a great start as we enjoyed the great weather, tasty food and thirsty quenching wine. About 45 minutes into the meal, we had just finished up our appetizers and were waiting for our pizza. The waiter then came out and asked us if we had already ordered a pizza or no? We said yes. So he then turned to the table next to us and asked them if they ordered the pizza. He was confused when they answered yes as well because the kitchen only had two orders in and there were three total pizzas (one for us, two for our neighbors). So he went back in and comes out with our neighbors pizza but alas, not ours. It turns out that they accidentally dropped our pizza ticket on the ground so our order never made it through. This made our dinner longer, but not too much longer and they definitely made up for and got our pizza out quickly.   Now let's move on to the pizza, for this is what Pomo Pizzeria is known for is it not? Oh friends, the pizza is exactly what you hope for it. It tastes like it's straight from the streets in Italy. We got the Quattro Stagioni which has tomato, San Marzano DOP, mozzarella, fior di latte, sauteed mushrooms, Italian Sausage, etc. The bread was thin crust but soft and melted in my mouth. The crust was fluffy and soft. The pizza is definitely large enough to split and the combo of salad, bruschetta and pizza worked out perfectly. The reviews are right in saying that this pizza is absolutely excellent and comparable to the other great pizza places in the Valley.
